The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Bengal | Briefs
                                                                                                               BRIEFS
                  
	Krishnagar, April 1: A Nadia court today stopped the screening of the Bengali film Cha-llenge in Nabadwip for 16 days after a residents body complained about obscenity in the pictur-isation of a remixed version of the kirtan Bhaja Gauranga.    
	The director and producer have been asked to appear on April 17 for the next hearing. The Nabadwip Nagarik Adhikar Raksha Committee had alleged that the film hurt the sentiments of the followers of Sri Chaityana by showing girls in skimpy dresses dan-cing to the revered song. The outfit had stopped the screening of the film midway in a theatre on Saturday        
	Chinsurah: Sunil Kumar Yadav, 28, a guard posted at the abandoned Nano project site in Singur, was found dead on Wednesday morning in the barracks near the erstwhile engine shop. His colleagues called police when he did not wake up from sleep. The body was taken to the Serampore Walsh Hospital, where doctors said he possibly had a heart attack. The body has been sent for post-mortem.        
	Barasat: Four-time MP and CPI candidate from Basirhat, North 24-Parganas, Ajay Chakraborty, was heckled by alleged Trinamul Congress supporters on Tuesday night. He was at Minakhan, 50km from Calcutta, to campaign when a mob blocked his way, banged his car and blamed him for lack of development in the area. Chakraborty told the police Trinamul was behind the protests.         
	Durgapur: The headless body of Utpal Dhibar, 23, son of a retired Durgapur Projects Ltd employee, was found off the railway tracks near the township. Utpal, an LIC agent, was missing since Tuesday. Police suspect he committed suicide and dogs or jackals took away the head.                                                                                                                                                                       
